Phenology Flagging

Megan Vahsen

2023-04-17

Description

This document details the code that informs how phenology data from the Bromecast 2022 experiments are flagged. The functions that are used to flag the phenology data are in the file QAQC_functions.R and are described in detail below.

  1. Late emergence: Notes if the plant emerged after the first date plants were assessed for emergence, and if so, records the date of the visit where emergence was first observed. NAs for plants with recorded emergence on the first visit and for plants that never emerged.
flag_lateemergence <- function(plant_data){
  # was plant absent first visit, later present?
  if(plant_data$live[1]=="Y"){
    return(NA)  # emergence on first visit
  }else if(sum(plant_data$live=="Y")==0){
    return(NA)  # never emerged
  }else{
    # return date of first recorded presence
    tmp <- which(plant_data$live=="Y")
    if(length(tmp)>1) tmp <- tmp[1] 
    return(plant_data$jday[tmp])
  }
}
  1. Emergence date: Records emergence date. NAs for plants that never emerged.
get_emergence_date <- function(plant_data){
  # date of first presence
  if(sum(plant_data$live=="Y")==0){
    return(NA)  # never emerged
  }else{
    # return date of first presence
    tmp <- which(plant_data$live=="Y")
    if(length(tmp)>1) tmp <- tmp[1] 
    return(plant_data$jday[tmp])
  }
}

  1. Death date: Records first date for which there absence recorded following a presence being recorded. Returns NAs if plants were alive and never died or if plants never emerged to begin with.
get_death_date <- function(plant_data){
  # date of first absence after a presence
  out <- NA  # death not observed
  tmp <- ifelse(plant_data$live=="Y",1,0) 
  tmp <- diff(tmp)
  deaths <- which(tmp==-1)
  if(length(deaths)>0){
      out <- plant_data$jday[1+min(deaths)]
  }
  return(out)
}

  1. Resurrection: Records if plant was recorded as being present after previously being recorded as absent. Returns NAs if plants were never recorded as absent after being present or if plants never emerged to being with.
flag_resurrection <- function(plant_data){
  # was plant observed alive after being observed dead?
  out <- NA
  tmp <- ifelse(plant_data$live=="Y",1,0) 
  tmp <- diff(tmp)
  births <- which(tmp==1)
  deaths <- which(tmp==-1)
  if(length(births)>0 & length(deaths)>0){
    if(max(births)>min(deaths)){
      out <- plant_data$jday[1+max(births)]
    }
  }
  return(out)
}

  1. Phenological regression: Determines if phenology goes backwards through time (e.g., V1 recorded after a previously recorded V2) and if so, records the maximum number of stages of regression for each plant. Returns NAs if phenological regression doesnt happen or if the plant never emerged to being with.
flag_phenoregress <- function(plant_data,pheno_table){
  # does phenology go backwards? returns how # of stages of regression
  out <- NA
  if(sum(plant_data$live=="Y")>1){
    plant_data <- merge(plant_data,pheno_table)
    plant_data <- plant_data[order(plant_data$jday),]
    tmp <- diff(plant_data$v_numeric)
    if(min(tmp)<0) out <- min(tmp)
  }
  return(out)
}

  1. Growth regression: Determines if the leaf length of the plant goes backwards through time and if so, records the maximum amount of shrinkage in millimeters. Records NAs if there is no growth regression or if plant did not emerge to begin with.
flag_growthregress <- function(plant_data){
  # does leaf length go backwards? return max mm of shrinkage
  out <- NA
  if(sum(!is.na(plant_data$length_mm)>1)){
    tmp <- diff(plant_data$length_mm)
    if(sum(!is.na(tmp)>0)){
       if(min(tmp,na.rm=T)<0) out <- min(tmp,na.rm=T)
    }
  }
  return(out)
}

  1. Frost heave: Determines if there was frost heave recorded for the plant and if so, returns the date of first recorded frost heave. Returns NAs if no frost heave recorded for the plant or if the plant never emerged to begin with. Also adds notes to observation about frost heave.
flag_frostheave <- function(plant_data){
  out <- NA
  # date of first frost heave
  tmp <- which(plant_data$frost_heave=="Y")
  # add notes about frostheave
  tmp <- c(tmp,which(plant_data$standard_note=="frostheave"))
  # return date 
  if(length(tmp)>0){
    tmp <- min(tmp)
    out <- plant_data$jday[tmp]
  }
  return(out)
}

  1. Herbivory: Determines if there was herbivory recorded for the plant and if so, returns the date for which herbivory was first recorded. Returns NAs if there was no herbivory recorded or if plants never emerged to begin with. Also adds notes to observation about herbivory.
flag_herbivory <- function(plant_data){
  out <- NA
  # date of first herbivory observation
  tmp <- which(plant_data$herbivory=="Y")
  # add notes about herbivory
  tmp <- c(tmp,which(plant_data$standard_note=="herbivory"))
  # return date 
  if(length(tmp)>0){
    tmp <- min(tmp)
    out <- plant_data$jday[tmp]
  }
  return(out)
}

  1. Bad position: Determines if the plant was not in the expected position and if so, returns the date for which bad position was first recorded. Returns NAs if there was no bad position: recorded or if plants never emerged to begin with. Also adds notes to observation about bad positioning.
flag_badposition <- function(plant_data){
  out <- NA
  # date of bad position observation
  tmp <- which(plant_data$standard_note=="badposition")
  if(length(tmp)>0){
    tmp <- min(tmp)
    out <- plant_data$jday[tmp]
  }
  return(out)
}

  1. Other notes: Determines if there are other standardized notes that are important to add to the derived data that are not herbivory, frost heave, or bad positioning, and if so, records them. If there are multiple notes, these are combined together. Returns NAs if there are no other notes.
flag_other <- function(plant_data){
  out <- NA
  # include other consequential notes
  tmp <- which(!is.na(plant_data$standard_note))
  if(length(tmp)>0){
    # remove frostheave, herbivory and badposition (these dealt with separately)
    tmp <- plant_data$standard_note[tmp]
    notes <- tmp[which(tmp != "herbivory" & tmp != "frostheave" & tmp != "badposition")]
    if(length(notes)>0){
      notes <- unique(notes)  # prevent duplicates
      notes <- paste(notes,collapse='-') # if multiple notes, combine
      out <- notes
    }
  }
  return(out)
}
